These articles particularly angered [[Arthur Weasley]] for her obviously biased reporting, and he, along with his son and fellow Ministry employee [[Percy Weasley]], had to head to the Ministry to help sort out the controversy, as she had mentioned Arthur in her article.<ref name="GOF10">{{GOF|B|10}}</ref>

====Triwizard Tournament====
{{Dialogue a-b-a-b|Harry Potter|I didn't. I don’t know how my name got into the Goblet of Fire. I didn’t put it in there.|Rita|Come now, Harry, there’s no need to be scared of getting into trouble. We all know you shouldn’t really have entered at all. But don’t worry about that. Our readers love a rebel.|But I didn’t enter. I don’t know who —|How do you feel about the tasks ahead? Excited? Nervous?|Rita Skeeter interviewing Harry Potter|Harry Potter and the Goblet of Fire}}
[[File:B4C18M2 Rita Skeeter interviews Harry.png|250px|thumb|Rita interviewing [[Harry Potter]]]]
That year, Rita was given the opportunity to interview the [[Triwizard Tournament]] contestants for an article in the ''Daily Prophet''. Under the guise of interviewing all four champions, she confronted [[Harry Potter]] in a broom cupboard where she took his "um"s and "er"s and used them as material to make her own quotes where Harry had said them. Eventually, her "interview of the contestants" turned out to be a highly falsified story of Harry himself.<ref name="GOF18">{{GOF|B|18}}</ref>

The article's falseness painted Harry as a tragic hero who cried himself to sleep over his [[Potter family|late parents]] and who had a romantic relationship with [[Hermione Granger]]. The article was mostly taken negatively by Harry's schoolmates, who assumed he was craving attention, although [[Molly Weasley]] seemed to take it very seriously, to the point that she was particularly cool towards Hermione for a time until Harry assured her that the article was lying and he and Hermione had never dated. At some point after the first task, Albus Dumbledore banned Rita from entering [[Hogwarts Castle]].<ref name="GOF21">{{GOF|B|21}}</ref>

====Interviewing Hagrid====
{{Dialogue a-b-a|Rita Skeeter|What are these fascinating creatures called?|Rubeus Hagrid|Blast-Ended Skrewts.|Really? I’ve never heard of them before... where do they come from?|Rita Skeeter interviewing Hagrid about his strange creatures|Harry Potter and the Goblet of Fire}} 
[[File:B4C21M1 cropped Rita Skeeter watching Care of Magical Creatures PM.jpg|250px|thumb|left|Rita watching a [[Care of Magical Creatures]] lesson focused on Blast-Ended Skrewts]]
Rita then interviewed [[Rubeus Hagrid]], asking many questions about Harry that Hagrid refused to answer.<ref name="GOF21">{{GOF|B|21}}</ref> Her subsequent article described Hagrid as a ferocious-looking man who used his authority to terrify his students, but this interview's quote information was otherwise mostly true and unchanged. The article also revealed to the world that Hagrid was actually [[half-giant]], which prompted letters from parents frightened by the idea of having a dangerous [[giant]] teaching their children and greatly upset Hagrid, subjecting him to ridicule and fear. 

However, his mood was rallied when Harry, [[Ronald Weasley|Ron Weasley]], Hermione, and Dumbledore visited him and assured him that they didn't care about [[Hagrid family|his family]] being the vicious monsters everyone believed them to be. Giants really were vicious and brutal, but Hagrid obviously wasn't, so Professor Dumbledore insisted Hagrid deny any insults and return to work, as Harry and his friends didn't care about Hagrid's family due to their knowledge of him as a person.<ref name="GOF24">{{GOF|B|24}}</ref>

Harry, Ron, and Hermione later overheard Rita discussing the possibility of writing an embarrassing story about [[Ludovic Bagman|Ludo Bagman]], Head of the [[Department of Magical Games and Sports]].

[[File:Tumblr mrtmk4u7no1r1d9g4o7 r1 250.gif|250px|thumb|''HARRY POTTER'S SECRET HEARTACHE'', published in ''[[Witch Weekly]]'' by Rita]]
When Rita encountered Harry, Ron, and Hermione in [[Hogsmeade]], Hermione insulted her for her libel. Rita, in retaliation, then wrote a nasty story about the "''devious Miss Granger''" based on false rumours provided by [[Pansy Parkinson]], making her out to be a plain but skilled witch who used [[Love Potion|love potions]] to satisfy her ''"taste for famous wizards''". Rita implied that Hermione was toying with the affections of both Harry and [[Viktor Krum]].<ref name="GOF27">{{GOF|B|27}}</ref> Although Hermione was more disdainful than upset about the article, she unfortunately started receiving [[Witch Weekly readers' hate mail to Hermione Granger|angry mail]] from people who believed Rita's lies. Some of the hate mail even came with [[jinx]]es and [[curse]]s.<ref name="GOF28">{{GOF|B|28}}</ref> Even Molly Weasley was upset with Hermione until Harry set her straight.<ref name="GOF18"/>

[[File:Harry-potter-goblet-rita, harry, and hermione.jpg|250px|thumb|left|Rita with Harry Potter and Hermione Granger in the tent during the first task]]
Rita's last defaming article stated that Harry was "''disturbed and dangerous''" and used comments from [[Draco Malfoy]] and his fellow [[Slytherin]] best friends as its basis.<ref name="GOF31">{{GOF|B|31}}</ref> Ultimately, Hermione discovered the means by which Rita spied on others and forced her to "''keep her quill to herself for a full year''" by catching her in her beetle form while she was perched on the [[Hospital Wing]] window and trapping her in a jar imbued with an [[Unbreakable Charm]] so she couldn't transform. 

Hermione blackmailed Rita by threatening to report her to the authorities at the [[British Ministry of Magic|Ministry of Magic]] as an unregistered [[Animagus]], which would have severe legal consequences. Rita was forced to comply, suffering financial strain as a result.<ref name="GOF37">{{GOF|B|37}}</ref> Unfortunately, her last article would discredit Harry and serve as the basis for [[Minister for Magic]] [[Cornelius Fudge]] to refuse to believe Harry's story about [[Tom Riddle|Voldemort's]] return, starting the Ministry's [[Campaign to discredit Albus Dumbledore and Harry Potter|smear campaign]] against both Harry and Dumbledore.

====''The Quibbler''====
{{Dialogue a-b-a|Rita|But of course, Little Miss Perfect wouldn't want that story out there, would she?|Hermione Granger|As a matter of fact, that's exactly what Little Miss Perfect does want.|You want me to report what he says about He-Who-Must-Not-Be-Named?|Discussion of Rita reporting Voldemort's return|Harry Potter and the Order of the Phoenix}}
[[File:Marygrandpre harry interview.jpg|250px|thumb|right|Rita Skeeter interviewing Harry Potter in the Three Broomsticks Inn]]
In [[1995]], Harry Potter's story that Lord Voldemort had [[Return of Lord Voldemort|returned]] was not believed by much of the [[wizarding world]]. Articles about his claims in the ''Daily Prophet'' portrayed him as either a delusional boy or an attention-seeking liar. Hermione Granger wanted to get the truth to the public and thus instructed Rita to meet her and [[Luna Lovegood]] in [[Hogsmeade]] on [[14 February]] [[1996]] in the [[Three Broomsticks Inn]]. As it was Rita who laid the foundation for the ''Prophet's'' defamation of Harry with her initial stories about him, Hermione wanted her to also be the one to set the record straight. They were joined by Harry after his date with [[Cho Chang]]. Harry thought that Hermione and Rita were "''the unlikeliest pair of drinking mates he could ever have imagined''".<ref name="OP25"/>

Rita was initially taken aback that Hermione wanted her to interview Harry, but then became resentful, since Hermione demanded that she only write exactly what Harry said and not portray him in a negative way. Rita claimed the ''Prophet'' would not buy the story, reluctantly admitting that the Ministry of Magic was influencing it. Hermione told her that the interview would be printed in ''[[The Quibbler]]'', which [[Xenophilius Lovegood|Luna's father]] edited. Although Rita responded with disdain, she "eyed Hermione shrewdly" for a few moments and then agreed. However, when she learned she was expected to conduct the interview free of charge, she was furious. Because Hermione was able to blackmail Rita with the threat of reporting her unregistered Animagus status to the Ministry, Rita grudgingly complied and wrote the article.<ref name="OP25">{{OOTP|B|25}}</ref>

The interview was subsequently printed in ''The Quibbler'', becoming its best-selling issue of all time. It was banned at [[Hogwarts School of Witchcraft and Wizardry|Hogwarts]] by [[Hogwarts High Inquisitor|High Inquisitor]] [[Dolores Umbridge]], which seemed to only increase its popularity.<ref name="OP26">{{OOTP|B|26}}</ref> Editor [[Xenophilius Lovegood]] sold the article to the ''Prophet'' after the [[Battle of the Department of Mysteries]], during which Voldemort's return became public, and he and his daughter Luna used the money to travel to [[Sweden]] in search of the [[Crumple-Horned Snorkack]].<ref name="OP38">{{OOTP|B|38}}</ref>

===''The Life and Lies of Albus Dumbledore'' {{C|1997}}===
{{Quote|Harry next recognised Rita Skeeter, who, he was infuriated to see, had a notebook clutched in her red-taloned hand.|Rita makes an appearance at Dumbledore's funeral|Harry Potter and the Half-Blood Prince}}
[[File:B6C30M1 funeral of Albus Dumbledore.png|250px|thumb|left|Rita was present at the funeral of Albus Dumbledore]]
Rita made a brief appearance at Hogwarts at the end of the [[1996–1997 school year]], where Harry was infuriated to notice her clutching a notebook at [[Funeral of Albus Dumbledore|Dumbledore's funeral]] in [[June]] [[1997]].<ref name="HBP30">{{HBP|B|30}}</ref> It was, perhaps, her being present at the funeral that prompted her to write a biography of Albus Dumbledore, as within four weeks, she wrote a 900-page biography about him, ''[[The Life and Lies of Albus Dumbledore]]'', which also included authentic old photos of the famed Hogwarts headmaster. Rita was interviewed by [[Betty Braithwaite]], a fellow ''Daily Prophet'' reporter, in her [[Rita Skeeter's home|home]], whom she treated very warmly, serving her tea and [[Pound cake]] and informing her of much gossip surrounding the book's release.<ref name="DH2">{{DH|B|2}}</ref>

[[File:RitaSkeeterBookSigning.png|250px|thumb|right|Rita promoting her new book]]
The book depicted the former headmaster in an extremely negative light, but was mostly based on truth, much to Harry's horror. It was implied that she got some of her information in unethical or illegal ways, as much of the book's content was obtained through an interview Rita conducted with [[Bathilda Bagshot]], a very elderly historian, where Skeeter used [[Veritaserum]] to gain information about Dumbledore's childhood. Skeeter stole photographs from Bagshot as well. The subsequent novel sensationalised everything, implying that Dumbledore had dabbled in the [[Dark Arts]] and contributed to the death of [[Ariana Dumbledore|his sister]].<ref name="DH18">{{DH|B|18}}</ref>

It turned out that Rita got at least some of her facts straight for once, but had no idea of the true story behind certain fabrications, such as her claiming that [[Ariana Dumbledore]] was a [[Squib]]<ref name="DH18"/> and that her mother was ashamed of her, when, in reality, she suffered from [[Obscurus|uncontrollable bursts of magic]] due to a highly traumatic experience when she was around six.<ref name="DH28">{{DH|B|28}}</ref>

