==Relationships==
===Harry Potter===
{{Dialogue|Rita Skeeter|Congratulations, Harry! I wonder if you could give me a quick word? How you felt facing that dragon? How do you feel now about the fairness of the scoring?|Harry Potter|Yeah, you can have a word. Goodbye.|Rita trying to get an interview with [[Harry Potter]] after defeating a dragon in the First Task|Harry Potter and the Goblet of Fire}}
[[File:Harry Potter movies hbp promostills 6.jpg|200px|thumb|[[Harry Potter]], whom she publicly shamed]]
Rita Skeeter first met Harry Potter in [[1994]] when [[Hogwarts School of Witchcraft and Wizardry|Hogwarts]] was housing the [[Triwizard Tournament]], during which Harry's name shot surprisingly from the [[Goblet of Fire]]. She immediately tried to get an interview with Harry, but did not get the chance until the the [[Wand weighing ceremony|Weighing of the Wands]], which she did inside a small broom cupboard. After the interview, she dedicated a whole page of the ''[[Daily Prophet]]'' for his interview, which greatly annoyed [[Amos Diggory]], the father of [[Cedric Diggory|Cedric]], another Hogwarts champion.

Shortly before the [[Dragon Challenge|First Task]], she tried to get another interview, but was interrupted by [[Viktor Krum]] and [[Hermione Granger]] and was told to leave. Skeeter ended up getting her revenge on Hermione several times after this in ''[[Witch Weekly]]'' and the ''Daily Prophet''. After Harry defeated the [[Hungarian Horntail]] and retrieved his [[Golden egg|egg]], Rita tried to get another interview, to which Harry refused. Harry did not see Rita Skeeter again until the next year, where he gave her an interview for ''[[The Quibbler]]'' announcing the return of [[Tom Riddle|Lord Voldemort]] and his [[Death Eaters]], which she did bitterly.

===Hermione Granger===
{{Dialogue a-b|Rita Skeeter|I'm supposed to do this ''for free''?|Hermione Granger|Well yes. Otherwise as you very well know, I will inform the authorities that you are an unregistered Animagus. Of course, the ''Prophet'' might give you rather a lot for an insider's account of life in [[Azkaban]]|Hermione forcing Rita to do an interview of Harry Potter about the return of [[Tom Riddle|Lord Voldemort]]|Harry Potter and the Order of the Phoenix}}
[[File:Hermione Granger Half Blood Prince.jpg|200px|thumb|left|[[Hermione Granger]], whom she disliked and publicly shamed]]
Rita Skeeter clashed with Hermione several times during both the Triwizard Tournament and during the denial of Lord Voldemort's return. She publicly shamed Hermione for her relationship with Viktor Krum and her supposed relationship with Harry Potter. When Hermione confronted and insulted Rita for having written horrible untruths about her friends, Rita vindictively responded by writing an article that painted Hermione as a "scarlet woman" who used her intellect and charm to toy with the affections of famous wizards. This caused Hermione to receive a large amount of [[Witch Weekly readers' hate mail to Hermione Granger|hate mail]], at least two of which were intended to cause significant harm to her, and be treated coldly by [[Molly Weasley]], who otherwise was very nice to her.

In return, Hermione furiously vowed to get revenge on Rita if it was the last thing she ever did. After researching for half a year about how Rita could possibly be getting her information despite being nowhere near and an unintentionally helpful hint from Harry, Hermione deduced that she was an unregistered Animagus and blackmailed her into keeping quiet for a whole year under threat of being exposed, which would otherwise land her in severe trouble.<ref name="GOF37"/> Hermione used this as leverage to get Rita to do an interview with Harry for ''The Quibbler'' without any charge. She called Hermione "Miss Prissy" and "Little Miss Perfect" due to her dislike of her.<ref name="OP25"/>

After the death of [[Albus Dumbledore]], Rita made her own biography about him called ''[[The Life and Lies of Albus Dumbledore]]'', which infuriated Hermione further.<ref name="DH18"/>

===Bathilda Bagshot===
[[File:Bathilda Bagshot profile.jpg|200px|thumb|[[Bathilda Bagshot]]]]
{{Quote|Dear Batty, Thanks for your help. Here's a copy of the book; hope you like it. You said everything, even if you don't remember it. Rita.|Rita Skeeter's note to Bathilda|Harry Potter and the Deathly Hallows}}
In [[1997]], Rita Skeeter travelled to [[Godric's Hollow]] to meet Bagshot and used [[Veritaserum]] to get vital information for her book on Albus Dumbledore. After this interview, she left Bagshot a small note and her own copy of ''The Life and Lies of Albus Dumbledore'', which was later taken by Hermione Granger and Harry Potter.<ref name="DH18"/> It is unknown whether Harry or Hermione kept the book, though it is unlikely that they did.

==Etymology==
*''{{W|Rita}}'' is a short form of the name ''Margarita'',<ref>[http://www.behindthename.com/name/rita Behind the Name: Rita]</ref> a Latinate form of the name ''Margaret''. The name is derived from the Greek μαργαρίτης, ''margarites'', meaning "pearl."<ref>[http://www.behindthename.com/name/margaret Behind the Name: Margaret]</ref>
*''Skeeter'' is a slang term for a "mosquito". This could be a reference to her [[Animagus]] form, which is an insect, her irritating personality, or to her career in tabloid journalism. The word ''paparazzi'' is derived from an Italian word for "mosquito".<ref>{{Wikilink|Paparazzi}}</ref> "Skeet" is also an Anglo-Manx colloquialism for gossip or an act of nosiness.<ref>{{Wikilink|Manx_English#Manx_loanwords|Manx loanwords}}</ref> Skeeter could also be a pun off of how annoying Skeeter's lies tend to be, as people tend to find mosquitoes annoying and attempt to swat them away.
*The character is similar to the "poison pen" biographer {{W|Kitty Kelley}}. Both have a semi-rhyming name with an animal reference and each is known for writing scandalous unauthorised biographies that largely consist of publishing every available unsubstantiated rumour about an individual. There is an interesting similarity in phrases used to describe the two authors. Skeeter was called "enchantingly nasty" by [[Albus Dumbledore]] in ''[[Harry Potter and the Goblet of Fire|Goblet of Fire]]'', and Kelley was called "encyclopedically vicious", by the [http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/6179623.stm ''New York Times''] while reviewing her biography of [http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/6179623.stm Nancy Reagan].

